Even if this is still an alpha version, I think it's already much better compared to the first alpha based on xl0.9.
For the workflows you need Math plugins for comfy (or to reimplement some parts manually).
Basically I do the first gen with DreamShaperXL, then I upscale to 2x and finally a do a img2img steo with either DreamShaperXL itself, or a 1.5 model that i find suited, such as DreamShaper7 or AbsoluteReality.

What does it do better than SDXL1.0?

  • No need for refiner. Just do highres fix (upscale+i2i)

  • Better looking people

  • Less blurry edges

  • 75% better dragons ğŸ‰

  • Better NSFW

Old DreamShaper XL 0.9 Alpha Description

Finally got permission to share this. It's based on SDXL0.9, so it's just a training test. It definitely has room for improvement.

Workflow for this one is a bit more complicated than usual, as it's using AbsoluteReality or DreamShaper7 as "refiner" (meaning I'm generating with DreamShaperXL and then doing "highres fix" with AR or DS7).

Results are quite nice for such an early stage.

I might disable the comment section as I'm sure some people will judge this even if it's early stage. I also don't think this is on par with SD1.5 DreamShaper yet, but it's useless to pour resources into this as SDXL1.0 is about to be released.

items.name: Helen Mirren (1978-83 era - CHECKPOINT)
items.description:
THERE IS A LORA VERSION OF THIS MODEL AVAILABLE. IT IS EXACTLY THE SAME MODEL AS THIS ONE, EXCEPT IN A DIFFERENT AND LIGHTER FORMAT.

Shivam Dreambooth of British actress and 1970s/80s sex symbol Helen Mirren, using 316 ref images and 1400 (real) reg images. This model is a merge between two of my own models of Mirren, from the period 1977-84 approximately. The first model is body-centered, with high detail on face, and the second concentrates on producing camera-facing poses. The average number of steps between the models was 12,000.

The period covered is around 1970-1985. To get a generation of the younger version, put the word young in front of the key prompt, and use brackets to control the degree of youth.

I generally use these models in complex workflows, inpainting faces after initial T2Is, and using ControlNet extensively. So if you're hoping for one-click prompt magic, my models aren't data-curated with this in mind, but rather as tools for traditional workflows that use Photoshop and other older methods.

This model may well produce subject-accurate NSFW output unless countered in negative prompts.

items.name: Semla Style - Swedish Semlor
items.description:
Nothing beats the traditional Swedish semla!

A wheat flour bun, flavored with cardamom, filled with almond paste and whipped cream, with some sprinkled powdered sugar on top. Bake it yourself: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G6EsiH5oYyE

Use the trigger word: "SemlaStyle" along with the LoRA to use it.

Recommended weights: 0.5-0.7 It's a bit over-baked :)

Recommended sampler: Euler-a

Note: It's actually not good at making a traditional semla. It will always fancy-it-up as it's trained on semla shapes, not normal semlas.

Note: Not all v1 preview images are from the final v1 merge. You may get a different generation, but it should be good.

Undesired results? If you end up with a stack of semlas, try describing your item differently or in more detail. This is how it acts when it doesn't know what to do with your prompt.

We are not having that discussion here, but from a purely technical perspective, this makes a smooth slider like this hard to make without first training on more gender neutral / non binary people, which this does not do. Most of my sliders are only trained on the existing knowledge in the model and they do not change what it knows, only how it associates it. Because of this, you will rarely get a smooth transition from male -> gender neutral -> female, and instead will generally have a hard switch from boobs to a hairy chest at some point.
